 He proposed at the Eiffel Tower in Paris.

5
00:00:12,400 --> 00:00:14,960
 Bro, she plays in his fantasy football league

6
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:17,160
 and knows more about the Cowboys than he does.

7
00:00:17,160 --> 00:00:19,520
 She's got the husband, the house.

8
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:20,920
 She's got it all.

9
00:00:20,920 --> 00:00:22,200
 What more could you ask for?

10
00:00:28,520 --> 00:00:31,880
 How are we this evening?

11
00:00:31,880 --> 00:00:33,120
 Come on.

12
00:00:33,120 --> 00:00:34,960
 Well, we're so glad you're here.

13
00:00:34,960 --> 00:00:39,360
 I grew up on a farm in a small town in South Texas,

14
00:00:39,360 --> 00:00:41,800
 so about 20 acres in the middle of nowhere.

15
00:00:41,800 --> 00:00:44,480
 And we had this big shed.

16
00:00:44,480 --> 00:00:46,280
 We called it the big garage.

17
00:00:46,280 --> 00:00:49,840
 And as I was a child and loved to play outside and be outside

18
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:54,000
 and whatnot, the big garage was just full of toys.

19
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,200
 And by toys, I mean like shovels and rakes and farming

20
00:00:57,200 --> 00:00:58,640
 equipment, that kind of thing.

21
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:01,120
 And there was this thing in there

22
00:01:01,120 --> 00:01:03,200
 that I didn't know exactly what it was,

23
00:01:03,200 --> 00:01:07,280
 but it instantly became a toy of mine, if you will,

24
00:01:07,280 --> 00:01:09,120
 because it kind of looked like a gun.

25
00:01:09,120 --> 00:01:11,160
 And so it would make this clicking noise.

26
00:01:11,160 --> 00:01:13,880
 And so I would get it, and I would kind of

27
00:01:13,880 --> 00:01:16,320
 go around the yard and pretend like I was shooting things.

28
00:01:16,320 --> 00:01:18,480
 And if a friend came over, I would give him one,

29
00:01:18,480 --> 00:01:19,080
 and I'd have one.

30
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:20,440
 And we would play kind of armies.

31
00:01:20,440 --> 00:01:21,800
 I think I've got a picture of it.

32
00:01:21,800 --> 00:01:22,520
 There it is.

33
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:23,600
 OK, so that's it.

34
00:01:23,600 --> 00:01:25,520
 And so that was this thing in the garage.

35
00:01:25,520 --> 00:01:27,160
 And so I would get it and play with it.

36
00:01:27,160 --> 00:01:30,080
 And so that's your kind of imagination runs.

37
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:31,880
 And so you ever see something, you're like,

38
00:01:31,880 --> 00:01:33,360
 I wonder what that's for.

39
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:35,880
 And so for me, I'm like, man, I wonder what that's for.

40
00:01:35,880 --> 00:01:39,320
 And so one day, I'm out with my dad,

41
00:01:39,320 --> 00:01:43,120
 and we're doing cowboy farming kind of stuff,

42
00:01:43,120 --> 00:01:45,800
 and not my kind of stuff, but his kind of stuff.

43
00:01:45,800 --> 00:01:46,720
 And so we're out there.

44
00:01:46,720 --> 00:01:47,960
 We're feeding the cows.

45
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:51,040
 And we stop by this fence that's broken.

46
00:01:51,040 --> 00:01:52,440
 And he gets out that thing.

47
00:01:52,440 --> 00:01:55,480
 And I'm like, dad, it's a weird time to play army man.

48
00:01:55,480 --> 00:01:56,400
 What are you doing?

49
00:01:56,400 --> 00:01:58,720
 And he hooks it up to the fence.

50
00:01:58,720 --> 00:02:01,040
 And he begins repairing the fence.

51
00:02:01,040 --> 00:02:03,240
 And so this is another picture of what it is.

52
00:02:03,240 --> 00:02:04,920
 And so that's what it's for.

53
00:02:04,920 --> 00:02:06,400
 And I remember having this moment--

54
00:02:06,400 --> 00:02:08,680
 this is why I tell you this weird story.

55
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:12,320
 I remember having this moment that's like, oh,

56
00:02:12,320 --> 00:02:14,320
 that's what that's for.

57
00:02:14,320 --> 00:02:15,320
 Like, I had no idea.

58
00:02:15,320 --> 00:02:17,520
 I would have never in a million years

59
00:02:17,520 --> 00:02:19,560
 been able to fill in the blank the right way.

60
00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:21,720
 It was like, oh, yeah, does that ever happen to you?

61
00:02:21,720 --> 00:02:23,480
 Oh, that's what that's for.

62
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:25,480
 Or like, you're doing something with something.

63
00:02:25,480 --> 00:02:26,920
 And you're like, that's not what that's for.

64
00:02:26,920 --> 00:02:28,720
 I'll go one more with you, because you guys

65
00:02:28,720 --> 00:02:31,240
 didn't seem to jump on board with the fence stretcher.

66
00:02:31,240 --> 00:02:33,000
 So let me go here.

67
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,880
 My son Weston comes in--

68
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:37,840
 about a year ago, he comes in the room.

69
00:02:37,840 --> 00:02:41,240
 And he's wearing Monica's bra on his head.

70
00:02:41,240 --> 00:02:44,040
 And he's like, earmuffs.

71
00:02:44,040 --> 00:02:46,800
 And I'm like, no, that's not what that's for.

72
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:48,880
 And I can't even show you what that's for, OK?

73
00:02:48,880 --> 00:02:50,960
 So we'll just talk about it.

74
00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:55,000
 So it's like there's something that serves a purpose.

75
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:57,720
 And you think that it serves a very different purpose.

76
00:02:57,720 --> 00:03:02,240
 And the reason I start there as we wrap up relationship goals

77
00:03:02,240 --> 00:03:05,760
 is because tonight, I hope that happens three times.

78
00:03:05,760 --> 00:03:12,200
 I hope three times tonight you go, oh, that's what that's for.

79
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:17,120
 I thought that it was just a toy for my amusement.

80
00:03:17,120 --> 00:03:19,260
 I thought that it was just something for me

81
00:03:19,260 --> 00:03:22,040
 to engage my emotions on.

82
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:26,480
 I thought that it was just a good time.

83
00:03:26,480 --> 00:03:30,840
 Oh, that's what that's for.

84
00:03:30,840 --> 00:03:36,320
 As we talk about singleness, being single,

85
00:03:36,320 --> 00:03:41,200
 dating, and marriage, I hope three times tonight you go,

86
00:03:41,200 --> 00:03:45,760
 oh, that's what that's for.

87
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:50,360
 We have to return to the purpose of these things--

88
00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:52,840
 being single, dating, and marriage.

89
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:55,080
 Because God, the creator of the heavens and the earth,

90
00:03:55,080 --> 00:03:56,960
 the one who formed you in your mother's womb,

91
00:03:56,960 --> 00:03:59,480
 the one who created all things as we know it and see it

92
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:06,400
 and live in it, has a purpose for singleness,

93
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:09,320
 and dating, and marriage.

94
00:04:09,320 --> 00:04:12,440
 And you would be infinitely better pursuing

95
00:04:12,440 --> 00:04:15,640
 his purpose than your own purpose, or the world's

96
00:04:15,640 --> 00:04:19,600
 purpose, or culture's purpose.

97
00:04:19,600 --> 00:04:21,980
 Because you've got to understand we're not getting better

98
00:04:21,980 --> 00:04:23,360
 at this.

99
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:27,600
 So the divorce rate right now is about 50%,

100
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:29,440
 depending on what stat you read.

101
00:04:29,440 --> 00:04:31,740
 Somewhere it's hovering around 50%.

102
00:04:31,740 --> 00:04:34,520
 That means about half of marriages fail miserably.

103
00:04:34,520 --> 00:04:37,640
 Half of people who says, I--

104
00:04:37,640 --> 00:04:40,240
 for richer or poorer in sickness and health

105
00:04:40,240 --> 00:04:44,400
 until death do us part, part before death.

106
00:04:44,400 --> 00:04:47,080
 About 50%.

107
00:04:47,080 --> 00:04:50,160
 And we're not getting better at this.

108
00:04:50,160 --> 00:04:53,680
 In fact, somebody after a couple weeks ago called in.

109
00:04:53,680 --> 00:04:54,880
 They wanted to talk to David.

110
00:04:54,880 --> 00:04:55,840
 They were upset.

111
00:04:55,840 --> 00:04:57,500
 Said they wouldn't be back to the porch

112
00:04:57,500 --> 00:05:00,440
 because we talked about this idea of cohabitating,

113
00:05:00,440 --> 00:05:02,020
 living together before you're married.

114
00:05:02,020 --> 00:05:03,840
 Said I'm committed to it.

115
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:06,800
 Well, let me share with you why a loving pastor would

116
00:05:06,800 --> 00:05:08,160
 tell you not to.

117
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:09,200
 I'll give you some stats.

118
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:12,660
 Greater than 60% of cohabitating couples who live together

119
00:05:12,660 --> 00:05:14,140
 do not get married.

120
00:05:14,140 --> 00:05:18,260
 Greater than 75% of cohabitating couples who get married

121
00:05:18,260 --> 00:05:19,140
 get a divorce.

122
00:05:19,140 --> 00:05:24,820
 What that means is 10 out of 100 couples

123
00:05:24,820 --> 00:05:30,420
 who cohabitated before marriage actually stay married.

124
00:05:30,420 --> 00:05:33,140
 10 out of 100.

125
00:05:33,140 --> 00:05:36,460
 And so a loving pastor and a loving God

126
00:05:36,460 --> 00:05:42,740
 would say you would be crazy to stack the odds against you

127
00:05:42,740 --> 00:05:44,100
 by doing-- and we said, well, no.

128
00:05:44,100 --> 00:05:45,740
 Isn't it going to be a better marriage?

129
00:05:45,740 --> 00:05:49,500
 No, statistically, absolutely not.

130
00:05:49,500 --> 00:05:52,540
 And when we talk about a divorce rate of like 50%,

131
00:05:52,540 --> 00:05:55,100
 for example, that does not account for those

132
00:05:55,100 --> 00:05:57,260
 who are miserably married.

133
00:05:57,260 --> 00:06:02,220
 So a successful marriage rate is much lower than 50%.

134
00:06:02,220 --> 00:06:03,600
 We're not getting better at this.

135
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:05,380
 We're getting married later.

136
00:06:05,380 --> 00:06:10,940
 On average, seven years later than in the 1960s.

137
00:06:10,940 --> 00:06:13,140
 Just a generation ago.

138
00:06:13,140 --> 00:06:14,820
 We're getting married seven years later.

139
00:06:14,820 --> 00:06:16,500
 What happens 50 years from now?

140
00:06:16,500 --> 00:06:18,740
 Seven years later and 50 years from there?

141
00:06:18,740 --> 00:06:20,140
 Seven years later?

142
00:06:20,140 --> 00:06:23,100
 Pretty soon we're getting married past the age

143
00:06:23,100 --> 00:06:24,580
 that people can have children.

144
00:06:24,580 --> 00:06:27,100
 Did you know that nearly half of girls

145
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:32,460
 who have children in their 20s are unmarried?

146
00:06:32,460 --> 00:06:34,500
 We're not getting better at this.

147
00:06:34,500 --> 00:06:37,220
 Seems like we've got to return to the purpose.

148
00:06:39,980 --> 00:06:43,340
 But what about if we do it God's way?

149
00:06:43,340 --> 00:06:46,340
 Another stat for you, Protestant Christian couples

150
00:06:46,340 --> 00:06:50,500
 actively involved in their faith are 35% less likely to divorce.

151
00:06:50,500 --> 00:06:56,180
 35% less likely to divorce than the general population.

152
00:06:56,180 --> 00:07:02,460
 93%, that's 93 out of 100 couples who independently

153
00:07:02,460 --> 00:07:04,660
 said that God is at the center of their marriage,

154
00:07:04,660 --> 00:07:09,700
 rated their marriage happy or very happy.

155
00:07:09,700 --> 00:07:13,140
 See, it seems to me that we forgot that we were created

156
00:07:13,140 --> 00:07:17,900
 by God for God to serve a purpose for God.

157
00:07:17,900 --> 00:07:20,220
 And if you had a Bible on a deserted island

158
00:07:20,220 --> 00:07:22,060
 and you began reading it and you said,

159
00:07:22,060 --> 00:07:24,340
 you know, I think this is kind of like God

160
00:07:24,340 --> 00:07:25,420
 has some things for me.

161
00:07:25,420 --> 00:07:27,420
 I want to understand how he wants me to date and pursue

162
00:07:27,420 --> 00:07:28,220
 relationships.

163
00:07:28,220 --> 00:07:29,220
 He's a relational God.

164
00:07:29,220 --> 00:07:30,460
 So I'm just going to read this like I'm

165
00:07:30,460 --> 00:07:31,780
 reading it for the first time.

166
00:07:31,780 --> 00:07:33,780
 I think that you're going to walk away

167
00:07:33,780 --> 00:07:35,620
 from that time on that deserted island

168
00:07:35,620 --> 00:07:39,500
 with a very different worldview of marriage, dating,

169
00:07:39,500 --> 00:07:40,380
 and singleness.

170
00:07:40,380 --> 00:07:46,900
 I think you're going to say, oh, that's what that's for.

171
00:07:46,900 --> 00:07:50,300
 I need to do that really, really different than I'm

172
00:07:50,300 --> 00:07:52,500
 doing that right now.

173
00:07:52,500 --> 00:07:56,100
 And so tonight, as we wind down relationship goals,

174
00:07:56,100 --> 00:07:58,700
 we're going to talk about the purpose of singleness,

175
00:07:58,700 --> 00:08:01,380
 the purpose of marriage, and the purpose of dating

176
00:08:01,380 --> 00:08:04,260
 and how it is very, very different than what you thought

177
00:08:04,260 --> 00:08:06,420
 when you came in this evening.

178
00:08:06,420 --> 00:08:08,540
 And so I want to show you that singleness is not

179
00:08:08,540 --> 00:08:11,060
 what you think, that dating is not what you think.

180
00:08:11,060 --> 00:08:12,700
 And before you leave here this evening,

181
00:08:12,700 --> 00:08:17,580
 that marriage is very different than what you think.

182
00:08:17,580 --> 00:08:21,140
 Monica and I do premarried couples, premarried counseling.

183
00:08:21,140 --> 00:08:23,780
 And so I've been in ministry for a decade now.

184
00:08:23,780 --> 00:08:26,260
 I've done about 40 weddings.

185
00:08:26,260 --> 00:08:29,020
 And by the grace of God, all 40 of those couples

186
00:08:29,020 --> 00:08:31,220
 are still married today.

187
00:08:31,220 --> 00:08:33,620
 And as we talk to them, all 40 of them,

188
00:08:33,620 --> 00:08:35,980
 as they sat in our living room, all 40 of them,

189
00:08:35,980 --> 00:08:40,940
 without exception, have had crazy expectations

190
00:08:40,940 --> 00:08:44,820
 around marriages, marriage that we've had to correct.

191
00:08:44,820 --> 00:08:46,980
 And they've all come back and said, man, you were so right.

192
00:08:46,980 --> 00:08:48,580
 We had these rose-colored glasses.

193
00:08:48,580 --> 00:08:52,380
 We had no idea what this would be like.

194
00:08:52,380 --> 00:08:55,780
 And so I want to help you this evening.

195
00:08:55,780 --> 00:08:58,260
 We're going to be in 1 Corinthians chapter seven,

196
00:08:58,260 --> 00:08:59,100
 if you want to turn there.

197
00:08:59,100 --> 00:09:01,540
 1 Corinthians chapter seven, written by the apostle Paul

198
00:09:01,540 --> 00:09:04,540
 to the church in Corinth about 56 AD.

199
00:09:04,540 --> 00:09:07,140
 The church is under great persecution.

200
00:09:07,140 --> 00:09:10,100
 He's using language like, hey, Jesus is returning soon.

201
00:09:10,100 --> 00:09:12,060
 You don't have long.

202
00:09:12,060 --> 00:09:15,260
 There's a sense of urgency to this letter.

203
00:09:15,260 --> 00:09:20,060
 Nero is about to show up on the scene, the emperor Nero,

204
00:09:20,060 --> 00:09:23,420
 and he is about to persecute Christians for sport.

205
00:09:23,420 --> 00:09:27,020
 He'll stitch animal skin to them, unleash dogs on them

206
00:09:27,020 --> 00:09:30,760
 so they can be ripped apart for the amusement of others.

207
00:09:30,760 --> 00:09:33,940
 And Paul writes to this church saying,

208
00:09:33,940 --> 00:09:35,580
 hey, get ready, troubles are coming,

209
00:09:35,580 --> 00:09:38,180
 and you need to understand,

210
00:09:38,180 --> 00:09:41,700
 you need to have a right perspective about singleness.

211
00:09:41,700 --> 00:09:43,760
 And he's going to talk about the betrothal period,

212
00:09:43,760 --> 00:09:46,100
 which is being engaged, which is the closest we have

213
00:09:46,100 --> 00:09:49,340
 to dating in the scriptures and marriage.

214
00:09:49,340 --> 00:09:51,260
 You need to have a right perspective of these.

215
00:09:51,260 --> 00:09:53,300
 Very applicable for them then,

216
00:09:53,300 --> 00:09:54,940
 very applicable for us tonight,

217
00:09:54,940 --> 00:09:58,500
 because we are moving in a culture facing persecution

218
00:09:58,500 --> 00:09:59,700
 for being a Christian.

219
00:09:59,700 --> 00:10:01,900
 Christian values, a biblical worldview,

220
00:10:01,900 --> 00:10:03,820
 is increasingly unpopular.

221
00:10:03,820 --> 00:10:07,060
 So this is a very applicable chapter for us this evening.

222
00:10:07,060 --> 00:10:09,240
 One of the longest chapters in the letter,

223
00:10:09,240 --> 00:10:11,260
 Paul's first letter to the Corinthians,

224
00:10:11,260 --> 00:10:13,900
 and it's written specifically about marital status.

225
00:10:13,900 --> 00:10:16,100
 Should I keep it, change it, or not worry about it?

226
00:10:16,100 --> 00:10:18,420
 He writes this in verse 28.

227
00:10:18,420 --> 00:10:21,020
 But if you do marry, you have not sinned.

228
00:10:21,020 --> 00:10:25,020
 And if a virgin marries, she has not sinned.

229
00:10:25,020 --> 00:10:27,860
 But those who marry will face many troubles in this life,

230
00:10:27,860 --> 00:10:29,940
 and I want to spare you of this.

231
00:10:29,940 --> 00:10:30,780
 What does he say?

232
00:10:30,780 --> 00:10:33,100
 Wait, those who marry will have lots of sex.

233
00:10:33,100 --> 00:10:33,940
 Wait, what is he?

234
00:10:33,940 --> 00:10:35,460
 He wants to tell us something about,

235
00:10:35,460 --> 00:10:39,800
 those who marry will have troubles.

236
00:10:39,800 --> 00:10:44,020
 In fact, this is the only marital guarantee in the Bible.

237
00:10:44,020 --> 00:10:49,020
 Those who marry will face troubles.

238
00:10:49,020 --> 00:10:52,380
 Okay, Paul, what else?

239
00:10:52,380 --> 00:10:55,980
 Verse 32, I would like you to be free from concern,

240
00:10:55,980 --> 00:10:58,360
 literally translated anxieties.

241
00:10:58,360 --> 00:11:02,140
 I would like you to be free from these worries.

242
00:11:02,140 --> 00:11:04,900
 An unmarried man is concerned about the Lord's affairs,

243
00:11:04,900 --> 00:11:07,540
 how he can please the Lord.

244
00:11:07,540 --> 00:11:09,060
 Speaking to single people.

245
00:11:09,060 --> 00:11:12,420
 Single people are concerned about the Lord's affairs.

246
00:11:12,420 --> 00:11:14,140
 They live to please the Lord,

247
00:11:14,140 --> 00:11:16,260
 but a married man is concerned about the affairs

248
00:11:16,260 --> 00:11:19,620
 of this world, how he can please his wife,

249
00:11:19,620 --> 00:11:21,300
 and his interests are divided.

250
00:11:21,300 --> 00:11:23,460
 An unmarried woman or virgin,

251
00:11:23,460 --> 00:11:26,500
 it's interesting that he just uses that synonymously.

252
00:11:26,500 --> 00:11:30,460
 Virgin would be like fiance or engaged.

253
00:11:31,580 --> 00:11:33,880
 And when he talks about an unmarried woman,

254
00:11:33,880 --> 00:11:35,620
 he just assumes in the scriptures,

255
00:11:35,620 --> 00:11:37,780
 writing to the church, that she's a virgin.

256
00:11:37,780 --> 00:11:39,540
 I don't say that out of condemnation,

257
00:11:39,540 --> 00:11:40,780
 but just to teach the text

258
00:11:40,780 --> 00:11:42,240
 so that you would have an understanding of it.

259
00:11:42,240 --> 00:11:44,260
 A virgin is concerned about the Lord's affairs.

260
00:11:44,260 --> 00:11:46,740
